{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.41,0.04,0.33,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1903"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6219"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"9587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43369"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents with discomfort in his left knee. He recalls experiencing a fall from his wheelchair a few days ago, resulting in an impact to his left knee. Over the past five years, he has mild joint discomfort affecting his wrists and the second and third metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, as well as his knees and elbows. This has been accompanied by episodes of morning stiffness, and the pain in these affected joints tends to wax and wane independently of one another. He also has underlying haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, his blood pressure is 126/86 mmHg, pulse rate 68/min, temperature 37.1\u00b0C and SpO2 99%. The left knee exhibits signs of redness, warmth, and swelling, with decreased active and passive range of motion. An X-ray of the left knee reveals some loss of joint space reduction and linear calcification of the articular cartilage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic arthritis","Calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease","Gout","Osteoarthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium pyrophosphate deposition (CPPD) disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by the deposition of calcium pyrophosphate crystals in joints. This condition primarily affects the elderly, with rare occurrences in younger individuals, usually when it is associated with other underlying diseases like hyperparathyroidism, hypothyroidism, or haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe majority of individuals with CPPD disease remain asymptomatic. However, CPPD disease is often referred to as the \u0022great mimic\u0022 because it can manifest in diverse patterns of joint disease among those who do develop symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPseudogout: Self-limited acute attacks of arthritis affecting one or multiple extremity joints. Often triggered by events like trauma, surgery, or severe medical illness. The knee is involved in 50% of cases, as in this particular case. Other joints typically affected include the wrists, shoulders, ankles, feet, and elbows.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPseudo-rheumatoid arthritis: Nonerosive, asynchronous, inflammatory arthritis that mimics RA. Associated with morning stiffness and malaise. This patient also has pseudo-RA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPseudo-osteoarthritis: Most common form of CPPD disease. Progressive articular degeneration in multiple joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECPPD disease primarily affects the knee and wrist, but in patients with haemochromatosis as the cause, arthritis often occurs over the second and third MCP joints, as observed in this case. The joint aspiration reveals weakly positively birefringent rhomboid-shaped crystals, while the X-ray displays chondrocalcinosis, characterised by punctate and linear radiodensities in the articular cartilage due to cartilage calcification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile\u003Cstrong\u003E septic arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eneeds to be ruled out due to the patient\u0027s history of acute onset of arthritis following a fall, the overall clinical picture, including the chronic joint pain and absent of pyrexia, is more suggestive of CPPD disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E, which closely resembles pseudogout, is more likely to affect smaller joints in the lower extremity, especially the first metatarsophalangeal joint. It often presents with subcortical bone cysts on X-ray, which are not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eusually affects larger weight-bearing joints and the spine, and in the hands, it involves the first carpometacarpal, DIP, and PIP joints. The wrists and MCP joints involvement in this patient aligns more with CPPD disease. Non-specific changes in x-ray such as loss of joint space are common in this age group and does not necessarily suggest OA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDifferentiating \u003Cstrong\u003ERA \u003C/strong\u003Efrom pseudo-RA in CPPD disease can indeed be challenging. In RA, joints tend to flare and remit simultaneously, which contrasts with the asynchronous inflammation seen in CPPD disease. Chondrocalcinosis is not a common feature of RA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["CPPD disease is characterised by the deposition of calcium pyrophosphate crystals in the joints and primarily affects the elderly.","While the majority of individuals with CPPD disease remain asymptomatic, the disease can manifest in various forms, including pseudogout, pseudo-OA, and pseudo-RA."],"references":["MacMullan P, McCarthy G. Treatment and management of pseudogout: insights for the clinician. Therapeutic advances in musculoskeletal disease. 2012 Apr;4(2):121-31. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3383522/","Higgins PA. Gout and pseudogout. JAAPA. 2016 Mar 1;29(3):50-2. https://journals.lww.com/jaapa/pages/articleviewer.aspx?year=2016\u0026issue=03000\u0026article=00009\u0026type=Fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-02T17:05:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-02T17:05:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40221"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"